# Command rg

## What does this command do:

ripgrep recursively searches directories for a regex pattern while respecting your gitignore

## Installed from

For Fedora install using: `sudo dnf install ripgrep`
For Raspberry Pi install using: `sudo apt-get install ripgrep`
For Mac install using: `brew install ripgrep`

## Command path

For Fedora run: `rg`
For Raspberry Pi run: `rg`
For Mac run: `rg`

## Command documentation

Docs can be found at https://github.com/BurntSushi/ripgrep

## Command options

# Basic search
rg <pattern>
rg <pattern> <path>

# Case insensitive search
rg -i <pattern>

# Case sensitive search
rg -s <pattern>

# Smart case (case insensitive if pattern is lowercase)
rg -S <pattern>

# Treat pattern as literal string (no regex)
rg -F <pattern>

# Show line numbers (default on)
rg -n <pattern>

# Print only filenames with matches
rg -l <pattern>

# Print only filenames without matches
rg -L <pattern>

# Print count of matches per file
rg -c <pattern>

# Print only matching portions of lines
rg -o <pattern>

# Invert match (show non-matching lines)
rg -v <pattern>

# Match whole words only
rg -w <pattern>

# Show context lines around match
rg -A 3 <pattern>   # 3 lines after
rg -B 3 <pattern>   # 3 lines before
rg -C 3 <pattern>   # 3 lines before and after

# Search specific file types
rg -t py <pattern>          # only Python files
rg -T py <pattern>          # exclude Python files

# Glob-based file filtering
rg -g '*.js' <pattern>      # include only .js files
rg -g '!*.min.js' <pattern> # exclude .min.js files

# Search hidden files and directories
rg --hidden <pattern>

# Ignore .gitignore rules
rg --no-ignore <pattern>

# Reduce filtering (-u: no .gitignore, -uu: no ignore files, -uuu: include binary)
rg -u <pattern>
rg -uu <pattern>
rg -uuu <pattern>

# Multiline matching
rg -U <pattern>

# Replace matches in output (does not modify files)
rg -r 'replacement' <pattern>

# Limit matches per file
rg -m 5 <pattern>

# Limit directory traversal depth
rg --max-depth 2 <pattern>

# Skip files larger than a size
rg --max-filesize 1M <pattern>

# Use multiple patterns
rg -e <pattern1> -e <pattern2>

# Read patterns from a file
rg -f patterns.txt

# Sort results
rg --sort path <pattern>

# Control thread count
rg -j 4 <pattern>

# Search compressed files
rg -z <pattern>

# Suppress output (exit code only)
rg -q <pattern>

# Print statistics
rg --stats <pattern>
